   Lyng Says Drought Could Prompt Relaxed Crop Acreage Controls Next Year The drought may force the government to ease crop acreage controls next year to help the United States rebuild its grain inventories, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said Monday.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The United States ``will continue to be a major player'' in world agriculture and in 1989 ``should be able to bounce back'' from this year's drought losses, he said.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Even with the severe drought, there will be an adequate supply of food grains and livestock feed grains so that the United States ``will be able to take care of our domestic needs and our export demand,'' he said.
